American art historian Elizabeth Hill Boone explores how indigenous artists and writers documented their ancestral culture. Analyzing the texts as one distinct corpus, Boone shows how they combined European and indigenous traditions of documentation and considers questions of motive, authorship, and audience. For Spanish authorities, she shows, the books revealed Aztec ideology and practice, while for the indigenous community, they preserved venerated ways of pictorial expression as well as rhetorical and linguistic features of ancient discourses. The first comparative analysis of these encyclopedias, Descendants of Aztec Pictography analyzes how the painted compilations embraced artistic traditions from both sides of the Atlantic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAztecszMexicovEncyclopediasy16th centuryvPictorial works. 0aAztecszMexicovEncyclopediasy16th centuryxAuthorship. 0aAztecszMexicovEncyclopediasy16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNahuatl languagexWritingxHistory. 0aPicture-writingzMexicoy16th century. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aAztec, art history, Aztec history, Indigenous cultures, Aztec society.  acosmology, colonization, colonial history, European art history, Aztec art, Spanish conquest.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074527640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32167640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477329351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477329351/original  a978-3-11-074527-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles